& [Inference] is bounded and restrained
  + [primary_observation] is n-domain smoothing creates a genuinely new bridge surface unlike discrete partial summation
  + [positive_result] is Cesaro improves the explicit-side smoothed bridge residual in all bounded rows and wins every best-kernel sample
  + [restraint_result] is the same Cesaro smoothing increases the exact finite cutoff residual against -zeta_prime/zeta, so the improvement is a bridge-surface smoothing effect, not a better approximation to the infinite target
  + [hann_result] is Hann gives smaller bridge improvement but less smoothing bias than Cesaro, making it a milder diagnostic surface
  + [identity_boundary] is no stronger explicit/Euler identity follows; smoothing exposes a bias tradeoff rather than a unified error law
  + [answered_question] is yes, Cesaro-style n-domain smoothing creates a new useful bridge diagnostic; no, it does not resolve the explicit/Euler boundary or prove a better zero-facing model
  + [next_reasonable_coordinate] is compare bias-corrected or two-parameter kernels only with a fresh source-defined contract, or pause this branch because the bridge tradeoff is now clear

  = must: treat Cesaro-Mellin smoothing as finite Re(s)>1 bridge-surface diagnosis only
  = must: report smoothing bias whenever reporting bridge-residual improvement
  = must: preserve sharp as the lower-bias finite cutoff baseline
  = must: treat Cesaro improvement as evidence of useful smoothing, not RH evidence or explicit/Euler identity
  - never: claim RH proof, disproof, independent zero certification, critical-line authority, universal bridge identity, or explicit/Euler fusion from this atlas

